abstract:
The first test of lepton flavour universality between muons and electrons
using $B^+ \to K^+\pi^+\pi^-\ell^+\ell^-$ ($\ell=e,\mu$) decays is presented.
The measurement is performed with data from proton-proton collisions collected
by the LHCb experiment at centre-of-mass energies of 7, 8 and 13 TeV,
corresponding to an integrated luminosity of $9\mathrm{fb}^{-1}$. The ratio of
branching fractions between $B^+ \to K^+\pi^+\pi^-e^+e^-$ and $B^+ \to
K^+\pi^+\pi^-\mu^+\mu^-$decays is measured in the dilepton
invariant-mass-squared range $1.1 < q^2 < 7.0~\mathrm{GeV}^2/c^4$ and is found
to be $R_{K\pi\pi}^{-1} = 1.31^{+0.18}_{-0.17}
\;(\mathrm{stat})\;^{+0.12}_{-0.09} \;(\mathrm{syst})$, in agreement with the
Standard Model prediction. The first observation of the $B^+ \to
K^+\pi^+\pi^-e^+e^-$ decay is also reported.
